#ad I always imagined I might slow down as I age. Well, I certainly did not…in fact, I wear more hats now than ever before! Sleep must be a priority for me to wear the hats of a businesswoman, blogger, wife, mother, grandmother, friend, Santa, hostess… all while managing my home after a major renovation!

I have learned from experience that I am most energized and ready to tackle the day after a night of quality sleep. Sleep is how I enjoy each day with youthful vigor!

If you struggle with insomnia and it is keeping you from living life to its fullest, please visit www.SeizetheNightandDay.com using the link in my profile.

Now, where did I put that Santa hat? Keep smiling and sleeping!

#Ad #PfizerSponsored  May is National Asthma and Allergy Awareness Month, and I am partnering with Pfizer to inform you about pneumococcal pneumonia and the importance for many of us to discuss this disease with our doctor or pharmacist...including me, as someone at increased risk for pneumococcal pneumonia due to my asthma.

Today, I am feeling grateful as the mother-of- the-groom for my son’s wedding this month. The preparations are complete, the dresses are hanging in my closet; the family is ready to welcome a wonderful new member to our crazy fun lives.

As I look ahead to this special day, I am taking my best shot at preventing pneumococcal pneumonia by staying up to date on my recommended vaccinations as a key part of my good health plan. 

Pneumococcal pneumonia is a potentially serious bacterial lung disease that can disrupt our lives for weeks. In severe cases, it can mean hospitalization and even be life-threatening.

Adults 65+ or those aged 19 or older living with certain chronic health conditions, such as diabetes, asthma, chronic heart disease, or COPD, among others, are at greater risk for pneumococcal pneumonia.

So, if you join me in these increased risk categories, then I encourage you to visit KnowPneumonia.com, linked in my bio, to learn more about the risk of pneumococcal pneumonia and talk to your doctor or pharmacist about pneumococcal pneumonia vaccination. Even if you have been vaccinated in the past, your healthcare provider may recommend another shot for additional protection against pneumococcal pneumonia.

Pneumococcal pneumonia shouldn’t stand in the way of taking your shot today and being part of special moments, just like my son’s wedding. This mother-of-the-groom will be smiling all the way.
@KnowPneumonia

#Ad #PfizerSponsored August is National Immunization Awareness Month, and I am partnering with Pfizer to show you how I take my best shot at travel and to enjoy life to its fullest.

When I travel, I insist on a great balcony view so that I can enjoy each sunrise and sunset outdoors and breathe in the fresh air.  These glorious views speak to me in special ways, and I do not want to miss any opportunity to see each destination’s beauty.

As a 70-year-old woman with asthma, I have worked with my doctor to determine a healthy lifestyle plan, which included a discussion on pneumococcal pneumonia and why vaccination is important to help protect my lungs.

Pneumococcal pneumonia is a potentially serious disease, and you are at greater risk if you are 65+ or 19 or older with certain underlying medical conditions such as diabetes, asthma, chronic heart disease, or chronic lung disease, among others.

Join me in making sure you have this important discussion with your doctor or pharmacist and visit KnowPneumonia.com at the link in my bio to learn more.

Take your best shot and don’t miss the beauty that waits for us outside. @knowpneumonia

Hello everyone!  I have been blogging about fashion, style and beauty for women in the second half of life for 14 years.

One big lesson I have learned is that impeccable style begins within us and not on the outside. I do not care what a woman is wearing or how her hair is styled, if she is unkind, arrogant, mean,  or nasty, she is NOT a woman with impeccable style.

It so grieves me to see women who are 50, 60,70 and beyond write nasty comments to fashion influencers.  We are the ones with experience and wisdom who should set examples of kindness for others. 

If your comment is not edifying, encouraging, or helpful....just do not write it.
Our voices are needed...more than ever...to help and not hurt.

Be a strong woman of impeccable style and set an example of kindness.
#kindess #kindnessmatters #styleover50 #styleover60 #impeccablestyle
